# Step 0: Why?
We are given data with multiple prediction variables and in the last column, a binary 1 or 0 depending on if the patient had a stroke. It seems like what we should do is use the variables we are given to predict whether or not a patient will have a stroke, so we can give better care to those who are predicted to have stroke from our model

# Step 1: Read the Data
We see many more 0s than 1s, this means that we should focus on the sensitivity of our confusion matrix rather than accuracy (just keep it in mind)
```{r}
data <- read.csv("stroke.csv")
#str(data)
prop.table(table(data$stroke)) # check imbalance between 0 and 1 in the stroke column
```

# Step 2: Transform the Data
## We see there are NA values, lets get rid of them
```{r}
data$bmi[data$bmi == "N/A"] <- NA #bmi has N/A instead of NA, convert it
data <- data[complete.cases(data), ]
data$bmi <- as.numeric(data$bmi) #bmi is char type, should be numeric
#str(data)
```
## ID is not relevent lets get rid of it
```{r}
data$id <- NULL
#str(data)
```
## Multiple variables must become factors since they are categorical variables 
```{r}
cols <- c("gender", "ever_married", "work_type", "Residence_type", "smoking_status")
data[cols] <- lapply(data[cols], factor)
str(data)
```

# Step 3: Split the Data
Just going to do a 70-30 split, no need for dummy data since no clusters
```{r}
ratio <- 0.7
set.seed(12345)

train_rows <- sample(1:nrow(data), ratio*nrow(data))
train <- data[train_rows, ]
test <- data[-train_rows, ]
```

# Step 4: Build the Model
Glm model with type as binomial since outcome is either 0 or 1. We will use our train data to train the model
```{r}
glm_model <- glm(stroke ~ ., data = train, family = binomial)
```

# Step 5: Predict
Have the normal 0.5 cutoff for predictions
```{r}
stroke_pred <- predict(glm_model, test, type = "response")
summary(stroke_pred)
stroke_binpred <- ifelse(stroke_pred >= 0.5, 1, 0)
```

# Step 6 Evaluate Model
Notice the high no information rate, which goes back to the large imbalance of 0 and 1 values. This means if we just guessed 0 always, we would get 0.9602 accuracy, so looking at overall accuracy may not be the best metric.

Instead see our high senestitvity of 0.96226, showing we still correctly predict stroke patients very accurately
```{r}
library(caret)
confusionMatrix(as.factor(stroke_binpred), as.factor(test$stroke), positive = "1")
```

